english:
  title: A Memorial on Current Affairs
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant has heard it said: "When the state enjoys peace, the words of ministers weigh no more than a feather; when the state faces crisis, the words of a common man weigh more than the sacred mountain." Though I am but a humble commoner, I dare to speak boldly. My folly and presumption deserve no pardon. Yet a dewdrop serves the heights, and the woodcutter's words have value to the sage. Should Your Highness graciously receive these words, the ancestral temple shall rejoice, and the nation's foundations shall endure.

    Your servant has heard that the proper ordering of boundaries and the equal distribution of fields are the first duties of governance. Our ancestors established systems of such completeness that nothing was left wanting. Yet over four hundred years, corruption has crept in like moss. The land system especially suffers. When boundaries blur, the powerful seize the weak's holdings—the crow nests where the magpie once lived. Though officials mark records in red, the strong claim what is theirs while the weak lose theirs. How many of these red-marked documents hide deception beneath them?

    Yet those who receive these lands are Your Majesty's servants, fulfilling their service through cultivation. What they gain compensates for what others lose—as when a man of Chu loses his bow, another man of Chu finds it. No harm is done.

    But the common people's heaven is the field. A family labors all year on their small plot to feed their parents and children, yet remains hungry. When the tax collector arrives, their meager harvest is already promised. If one landlord holds the deed, perhaps there is justice. But when three, four, seven, or eight families claim the same field, and each asserts their strength, who will yield? Thus the tenant pays rent but remains poor, and must borrow more to survive. How then do they feed their parents? How do they raise their children? The people's poverty flows from this corruption.

    The *Book of Poetry* laments: "The rich may yet find contentment, but pity the solitary poor." When Your Highness took the throne, you made the land system your first concern. You have issued pardons repeatedly, your decrees filled with careful thought and distant vision born of Your Majesty's own heart. How noble! Wishing for fish is inferior to mending nets. Gluing a harp's bridge cannot produce melody. Without reforming the system, its diseases cannot be cured.

    I humbly request that you take the registers from the *Gapjin* year as your foundation, consult the official records, correct disputed holdings, measure newly cleared lands, tax the new fields, and reduce the unjustly granted ones. Thus the state's revenue increases and disputed lands find peace. When farmers feel secure, the people's hearts gladden. When the people's hearts gladden and the state's revenue swells—this is what a wise ruler deeply desires. Why does Your Highness hesitate?

    Some say: "The wealthy's fields cannot be reclaimed suddenly, nor can ancient abuses be reformed overnight." Such timidity befits a mediocre ruler, not one whom we hold in such hope. Methods of implementation and refinement surely rest with your great ministers—I am but a young scholar and dare not presume. Yet whether this shall be done depends only upon Your Highness's sincerity.

    Recently, Japanese pirates have invaded our realm, causing His Majesty to lose sleep with worry. Our elder statesmen have consulted on our response and reached consensus on the essential measures. Yet your servant, mourning his father in a coastal province, has also reflected carefully on this matter. Two strategies present themselves: defending the land and waging naval war.

    As a cart cannot cross water and a boat cannot travel land, so human nature varies. The northern peoples endure cold; the southern peoples endure heat. Our inland farmers have never sailed—before stepping on a deck their spirits grow faint. At the first storm, they tumble left and right, too occupied with falling to stand and fight the enemy. How can they confront raiders with courage?

    For land defense, I propose conscripting farmers, sharpening their weapons, stationing them at strategic points, maintaining impressive formations and beacon fires to dazzle the enemy. Local magistrates can manage this. What use then is the Touring Inspector? He merely brings humiliation to officials and waste to the treasury.

    For naval warfare, I observe that our nation's three coastal regions shelter near a million island dwellers. Swimming and boating are their natural gifts. They live not by farming but by fishing and salt-making. Now, driven from their homes by these pirates and robbed of their livelihood, they harbor resentment ten-fold greater than inland folk. Send one rider bearing proclamations along the coast offering rewards—thousands will join in a day. Using their natural skill against those they hate, how could they fail to triumph? Moreover, what greater profit than the enemy's head? Let a Pursuit Commissioner lead them, always stationed on ships, and the regions will prosper while bandits are defeated. These two strategies are essential: land defense steadies our resolve; naval war intimidates the foe. Both together cannot fail.

    When the Han rose against the Chu, Xiao He planned strategy without ever riding to war—this was the civil art. Han Xin commanded troops and bore the warrior's burden—this was the martial art. When Liu Xiu restored the dynasty, he set down his spear to study the classics and rested his horse to discuss the Way. Thus he combined both talents perfectly, achieving what later generations cannot match. Even in times of war, we do not abandon scholarly pursuits—how much less can we forget military readiness in times of peace?

    Our ancestors knew this well. They established positions and offices, honored learning and valued martial prowess, never neglecting one for the other. Yet our realm has enjoyed a hundred years of peace. The people have forgotten warfare. The Ten-Thousand Household Corps exists only as an empty title from the Imperial Court. The offices of the Guard Regiments have become sinecures for the wealthy, with no soldiers at all. Compared to the ancients, though we speak of valuing martial affairs, we possess no actual martial force.

    Now the pirates have thrown the realm into turmoil. The people of the central plains have tasted the enemy's bitter salt. Only Heaven's mercy toward our Yuan master and Your Majesty's deep compassion toward the common people have preserved us from collapse. Yet even in safety, we must contemplate danger. As the saying goes: when a Chu man loses his ape, the calamity spreads to the forest; when the city gate catches fire, the disaster reaches the fish in the pond. How can we sit unmoved?

    Moreover, our nation has Japan to the east, the Jurchen to the north, and ships from the southern provinces to the south. We have only the path through the Middle Kingdom to the west. When pirates arrived, we were thrown into confusion, forced to seek military aid. If southern bandits sail northward or the Jurchen turn their horses south, shall the common people, bent beneath their plows, suddenly become soldiers? Should crisis strike suddenly, all would collapse, leaving none to defend the nation or support the throne.

    Thinking thus, your servant's heart grows cold. I humbly request that you establish a military examination, recruit soldiers for the Guard Regiments, test their valor and train their skills, grant them rank and salary to inspire their spirit. Thus the nation shall have sufficient soldiers and the people shall willingly serve, preventing future regrets.

    Once, Jia Yi wept and sighed even when Emperor Wen faced no crisis. How much more should we act when the fire already burns beneath us? Better that this humble servant face accusations of madness than that the Sacred Court face charges of unpreparedness. This is your servant's sincere wish.

    Regarding the Way of Confucius—it is vast and profound, beyond this servant's power to illuminate. The structures and practices of our ancestral temples and schools are likewise beyond my full understanding. Yet within our nation, we have established the National Academy with its Twelve Groups and the Eastern and Western Study Halls; without, each province and county maintains schools. Their scope is grand, their regulations detailed. Observing our ancestors' intentions, their exaltation of the scholarly way ran deep and earnest.

    The National Academy is the spring of moral transformation; human talent is the foundation of governance. Without nurturing, the root weakens; without deepening, the spring grows murky. Those ancient rulers who earned noble reputations throughout the realm all gave their hearts to this cause.

    Your Highness, blessed with the natural capacity of a sage and having long admired the Way of the ancients, sorrows over the decline of schools and has issued orders for their restoration. This benefits not merely us scholars—it brings true blessing to the common people. Yet students have scattered and dormitories crumble. There is reason for this.

    Your servant would speak thus: The ancients studied to become sages; today's scholars study to gain office. They recite poetry and read classics, yet their love of the Way runs shallow. They compete for worldly embellishment while moral sincerity decays. They carve ornate phrases while overlooking the cultivation of rectitude. Some grow old having achieved nothing, lamenting their wasted lives. How few among them become exemplars of scholarship or pillars of the state?

    The *Poetry* says: "How can virtuous rulers not cultivate worthy men?" The art of cultivating worthiness lies in the ruler's transformation. Yet with such decay among the scholars themselves, can those in power evade responsibility? Moreover, advancement to office does not require examination success, nor does examination success require studying at the National Academy. Who would abandon the shortcut for the long path? This is why students scatter and dormitories decay.

    I humbly request that you issue clear regulations: at the village level and within the academies, examine students' talents and advance the worthy through the Twelve Groups, then examine them collectively for advancement to the National Academy. Set time limits, test their virtue and learning, and report the qualified to the Ministry of Rites for official appointment and the unqualified for lesser positions. Forbid all but National Academy graduates from taking the examination. Thus those once reluctant to come shall be eager to stay. Your servant foresees talents emerging without end, providing Your Highness with an endless supply.

    When Buddhism entered China, princes and commoners alike honored and served it. From the Han to now, it has flourished day by day. When our Great Founder unified the realm, temples and homes stood side by side. Since the middle ages, monks have multiplied—five teachings and two schools have become dens of profit. By every stream and every hillside stands a temple. Not only have the monks grown base and lowly, but our nation's common people idle away their lives in idleness, causing all discerning men to grieve.

    Buddha was a great sage, and his preferences surely matched those of humankind. How could his departed spirit not feel shame at such disciples? I humbly request that you issue clear prohibitions: grant ordination documents even to current monks, but conscript those without documents into the military; order all newly built temples demolished, and punish magistrates who fail to comply. Thus you shall prevent the people from becoming wholly shaven-headed.

    Your servant has heard that Your Highness's devotion to the Buddha surpasses even your reverence for the previous sage-rulers, and that you pray ardently for the nation's long endurance—a noble and beautiful aspiration. Yet in your servant's humble judgment, Buddha is supremely holy and impartial—he rejoices not if honored to excess, nor grows angry if treated with restraint. Moreover, his own scriptures plainly state: "The merit of charity does not equal that of reciting sutras." In your hours of leisure from governance, if you turn your attention to these teachings and devote yourself to sudden enlightenment, there is no harm. Yet those in high station set the example for all; waste squanders the treasury. We must block the leak before it becomes a torrent.

    Confucius taught: "Revere the spirits and demons, yet keep them at distance." Your servant would have you maintain the same relationship with the Buddha. I know that offending Your Majesty's sensibilities brings the risk of execution. Yet fearing that unchecked indulgence might overflow like a stream bursting its banks, I dare speak at the cost of my life.

    Your servant further reflects that flourishing and decline arise from natural causes. Our nation has suffered two generations of child-rulers while powerful regents wielded authority, allowing the state's framework to crumble. The people long for good governance. Your Highness, possessed of keen wisdom and generous temperament, has the capacity for great deeds. You have come when disorder reaches its height, when governance must be restored—a time when worthy men are urgently needed. Yet I have not seen you eagerly seeking the counsel of the virtuous. You have taken power when politics demands immediate attention, yet I have not seen the hall lamps burning bright with your engagement. Are all able men appointed? Have all schemers been banished? I hear of no policies implemented, only of the people's disappointed hopes.

    To expect good governance thus is like walking backward while hoping to advance, like turning one's cart south to reach the north. Your servant is deeply ashamed on your behalf.

    The *Book of Changes* teaches: "Heaven's constant movement is vigorous; thus the superior man perpetually strengthens himself without ceasing." There is no greater principle for cultivating the heart or conducting governance. I beg Your Highness to keep this close to heart.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The *Gapjin* year (甲寅) refers to a specific year in the recording of land registers, likely 1374, when Lee Saek's memorial was presented.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Ten-Thousand Household Corps' (万戶府) was a military administrative unit established by the Yuan dynasty but had become an empty title in Goryeo by this period.
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Teachings and Two Schools (五敎兩宗) refer to different Buddhist doctrinal divisions—the Five Teachings of the Huayan school and the two main Korean Buddhist schools, Tianatai and Caodong (called Seon in Korea).
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Saek uses the metaphor of Xiao He (蕭何) and Han Xin (韓信) to illustrate the complementary roles of civil and military leadership in the founding of the Western Han.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Touring Inspector' (都巡問使) was an imperial oversight position that Lee Saek suggests adds bureaucratic burden without practical military benefit.
